iction in the nineteenth century, and a general turn from didacticism to entertainment. Literary scholars, historians, and anyone who wishes to know more about Chinese popular culture in the Qing dynasty will benefit from reading this book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aChinese fictionyQing dynasty, 1644-1912xHistory and criticism. 0aMartial arts fiction, ChinesexHistory and criticism. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Literature. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Literary History. 4aLiterature : Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978079147705240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791477052423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791477052/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles